<p>Well, Mrs. Banerjee was responsible for most of those characters and plots. She made them come alive in the History and English lessons. She taught me how to browse through library books making me fall in love with that space. She taught me the habit of sleeping with books and a dictionary under my pillow. I still do.</p>
<p>The red and blue pages always had a valuable remark at the end. Sometimes it would tell me to begin each line exactly below the previous one. Sometimes it would tell me to use â€˜theirâ€™ and â€˜thereâ€™ correctly. Sometimes it would tell me to frame the letters â€˜bâ€™ and â€˜fâ€™ more legibly. Sometimes she would point to the overwhelming use of conjunctions and so on. â€˜Avoid those giants of letters. Let me see the Lilliputians in your notebook,â€™ said one of her remarks. Perhaps even Jonathan Swift couldnâ€™t have imagined Lilliputians of Gulliverâ€™s Travels as custodians of hand-writing!</p>
<p>The red and blue notebook super heroes created by my favourite teacher gave me a legible hand-writing, my love for reading, and also the bugs infested in my pen. I could barely ever use organisation ideas for my writing pieces though she tried very hard. I still mostly canâ€™t. My pen seems to be on a trip of its own. I can sense the bugs as they take over each time I write...</p>
